{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630977"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17337"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.08,0,0.32,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10027"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57140"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6846"},{"type":"tags","id":"7414"},{"type":"tags","id":"8138"},{"type":"tags","id":"9154"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23488"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA woman presents with a three-month history of a painless lump in her lower abdomen that becomes more prominent when she sits up from lying down. On examination, there is a 3 cm smooth, firm, non-tender mass in the midline of her anterior abdominal wall, 4 cm below the umbilicus. The mass becomes more prominent with a sit-up manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical location of this mass?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subcutaneous layer superficial to muscle","Lateral abdominal wall between muscle layers","Deep to internal oblique muscle","Deep to transversalis fascia","Within the rectus sheath"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical presentation suggests a rectus sheath hernia. The mass is located \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep to transversalis fascia\u003C/strong\u003E. Below the arcuate line (located halfway between the umbilicus and pubic symphysis), the posterior rectus sheath is absent, making this area susceptible to herniation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous layer superficial to muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - This location would be too superficial for a rectus sheath hernia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral abdominal wall between muscle layers\u003C/strong\u003E - The mass is in the midline, not in the lateral abdominal wall\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep to internal oblique muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - This would place the mass in the lateral abdominal wall, not the midline where it was found\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithin the rectus sheath\u003C/strong\u003E - Below the arcuate line, there is no posterior rectus sheath, and the mass lies deeper than this level\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe location of this mass is consistent with the anatomical arrangement below the arcuate line, where the rectus abdominis muscle lies directly on the transversalis fascia and peritoneum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The rectus abdominis muscle is enclosed within the rectus sheath, which is composed of aponeurotic layers from three abdominal wall muscles.","The posterior wall of the rectus sheath terminates at the arcuate line, located midway between the umbilicus and pubic bone.","The rectus abdominis has no posterior sheath coverage inferior to the arcuate line, lying against transversalis fascia."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57140"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17337"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57140"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T09:04:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T09:05:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10027"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71644"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"